    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Glenn C. Gillespie was born on a farm in Addison Township, Oakland County Michigan, June 10, 1885.  He worked as a telegraph operator to as  young ma before graduating from the University of Michigan Law School in 1910.  He opened a law  practice I Pontiac, Michigan where he resided for the rest of his life.  In 1921 he named a judge of the Sixth Judicial  Circuit of Michigan.  He served as s judge for 15 years  before returning  to private practice.  He was recognized a  leading authority on criminal law and procedure.  He was a founding member and first president of the  State Bar Association.</p>
      <p>Gillespie was an avid hunter fisherman and aviation enthusiast.  He died March 11, 1959 in automobile accident in Bristow, Oklahoma.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Gillespie papers consist of clippings and miscellaneous items relating to his legal career and articles on his death, photographs, judicial opinions and films.</p>
      <p>The Photographs consist of  portraits  and s composite photos of Oakland County Bench and Bar, 1924 and 1950, and a folder of copy prints of photos from the two albums.  The albums  contain numerous images of hunting  and fishing scenes, many frorm Houghton Lake and the Au Sable River, oil rigs in Genesee county,  the Detroit Ski Club ski jump in Rochester, Michigan, photos of the First and Second Michigan Air Tours, 1929 and 1931, view of Mackinaw City, Mich storefronts, 1917, Ranger, Texas, street views and oil rigs, 1919, vacation at Isle Royale, Mich., 1935, and a trip to the Soo Locks and Tahquamenon Falls.</p>
      <p>The Judicial Opinions Series includes all of he opinions Gillespie wrote as a member of the Sixth Judicial Circuit Court of Michigan, 1921-1934</p>
      <p>The Motion Pictures series consists of two 16mm films documenting portions of the First and Second Michigan Air Tours, 1929-1930, including footage of airplanes and aerial views of Michigan scenes; includes views of Governor Fred Green, the airship Graf Zeppelin, and Mackinac Island  The films were digitized in 2011 and are now available on DVD or as streaming files (on request).</p>
    </scopecontent>
